    <section id="learn-tab" class="tab-pane active">
      <div class="article-layout">
        <article class="scitable-article">
          <div class="article-hero">
            <span class="article-category">Topic Room: Nucleic Acid Structure & Function</span>
            <h1 class="article-title">Translation: DNA to mRNA to Protein</h1>
            <div class="article-meta">
              <span class="author-avatar"><i class="fa-solid fa-user-doctor"></i></span>
              <div class="author-info">
                <p class="author-name">Redesigned from Clancy, S. & Brown, W. (2008)</p>
                <p class="citation-detail">Nature Education 1(1):101 • Updated with 3D Ribosome Simulations</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
          
          <div class="article-body">
            <p class="lead-paragraph">
              How does the cell convert DNA into working proteins? The process of translation can be seen as the decoding of instructions for making proteins, involving mRNA in transcription as well as tRNA.
            </p>
            
            <div class="article-divider"></div>
            
            <h2>1. The Flow of Genetic Information</h2>
            <p>
              The genes in DNA encode protein molecules, which are the "workhorses" of the cell, carrying out all the functions necessary for life. For example, enzymes, including those that metabolize nutrients and synthesize new cellular constituents, as well as DNA polymerases and other enzymes that make copies of DNA during cell division, are all proteins.
            </p>
            <p>
              In the simplest sense, expressing a gene means manufacturing its corresponding protein, and this multilayered process has two major steps:
            </p>
            
            <!-- Dynamic Mini-Visualizer Card -->
            <div class="interactive-card central-dogma-card">
              <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-circle-nodes"></i> Central Dogma Interactive Overview</h3>
              <div class="dogma-flow">
                <div class="dogma-node dna-node">
                  <div class="node-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-dna"></i></div>
                  <span class="node-title">DNA</span>
                  <span class="node-desc">Double Helix (Information Store)</span>
                </div>
                <div class="dogma-arrow">
                  <i class="fa-solid fa-arrow-right"></i>
                  <span class="arrow-label">Transcription</span>
                </div>
                <div class="dogma-node rna-node">
                  <div class="node-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-note-sticky"></i></div>
                  <span class="node-title">mRNA</span>
                  <span class="node-desc">Single Strand (Messenger)</span>
                </div>
                <div class="dogma-arrow">
                  <i class="fa-solid fa-arrow-right"></i>
                  <span class="arrow-label">Translation</span>
                </div>
                <div class="dogma-node protein-node">
                  <div class="node-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-cubes"></i></div>
                  <span class="node-title">Protein</span>
                  <span class="node-desc">Polypeptide (Functional Unit)</span>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <p>
              During <strong>transcription</strong>, the DNA of a gene serves as a template for complementary base-pairing, and an enzyme called <strong>RNA polymerase II</strong> catalyzes the formation of a pre-mRNA molecule, which is then processed to form mature mRNA. The resulting mRNA is a single-stranded copy of the gene, which next must be translated into a protein molecule.
            </p>
            <p>
              During <strong>translation</strong>, the mRNA is "read" according to the genetic code, which relates the DNA sequence to the amino acid sequence in proteins. Each group of three bases in mRNA constitutes a <strong>codon</strong>, and each codon specifies a particular amino acid (hence, it is a triplet code).
            </p>
            
            <h2>2. Where Translation Occurs</h2>
            <p>
              Within all cells, the translation machinery resides within a specialized organelle called the <strong>ribosome</strong>.
            </p>
            
            <div class="coupled-note-card">
              <h4><i class="fa-solid fa-dna"></i> Prokaryotes vs. Eukaryotes</h4>
              <div class="split-comparison">
                <div>
                  <h5>Eukaryotic Organisms</h5>
                  <p>Mature mRNA molecules must leave the nucleus and travel to the cytoplasm, where the ribosomes are located. Transcription and translation are temporally and spatially separated.</p>
                </div>
                <div class="border-left">
                  <h5>Prokaryotic Organisms</h5>
                  <p>Ribosomes can attach to mRNA while it is still being transcribed. Transcription and translation are <strong>coupled</strong>, occurring simultaneously in the same compartment.</p>
                </div>
              </div>
            </div>

            <h2>3. The Ribbon of Life: tRNA & The Ribosome</h2>
            <p>
              The ribosome is composed of a large subunit (50S in prokaryotes, 60S in eukaryotes) and a small subunit (30S in prokaryotes, 40S in eukaryotes). Inside, there are three active sites where tRNA molecules dock: the <strong>A (Aminoacyl) site</strong>, the <strong>P (Peptidyl) site</strong>, and the <strong>E (Exit) site</strong>.
            </p>
            <p>
              The transfer RNA (tRNA) acts as the physical link between the mRNA code and the amino acid chain. Each tRNA has an <strong>anticodon loop</strong> that is complementary to the mRNA codon, and holds the matching amino acid on its 3' acceptor stem.
            </p>
            
            <div class="article-cta-box">
              <h4>Want to see it in action?</h4>
              <p>Skip to our fully animated simulator tabs to interact with transcription bubbles, watch the ribosome peptide transfer cycle, or simulate mutational frame shifts.</p>
              <div class="cta-buttons">
                <button class="cta-btn primary-cta" onclick="document.getElementById('btn-tab-transcribe').click()"><i class="fa-solid fa-scissors"></i> Open Transcription</button>
                <button class="cta-btn secondary-cta" onclick="document.getElementById('btn-tab-translate').click()"><i class="fa-solid fa-gears"></i> Open Translation</button>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </article>
        
